Condition Other Description: Impaled on vertical metal post on oil rig
Additional Remarks: Justin Viezbicke emailed CIMWI on 9/25 with photos and a description of the situation. An adult male California sea lion had impaled itself on a vertical post on an oil platform in the ocean off of Santa Barbara. Dr. Dover and team responded the following day and successfully removed the animal from the post and released it immediately. 48 hours later, the oil platform communicated that the animal had expired.
Note: this observation was associated with but occurred BEFORE the launch of a Falcon 9 rocket from Vandenberg AFB. Heavily scavenged prior to observation.

Vandenberg AFB launched a Falcon 9 rocket on 6 October 2018, but this was discovered "relatively fresh" with little decomposition and scavenging more than 9 days later, we have no reason to believe the mortality was in any way related to the rocket launch.

Locality Detail: 1/2 NAUTICAL MILE SOUTH OF SANTA BARBARA ISLAND
How Determined: Describe: VESSEL CREW FELT THE IMPACT OF THE SEA LION AND OBSERVED THE SINKING CARCASS
Additional Remarks: DURING A TRANSIT AT 16KTS, THE NOAA RESEARCH VESSEL SHEARWATER STRUCK A CALIFORNIA SEALION, 1/2 NM SOUTH OF SANTA BARBARA ISLAND. THE CAPTAIN, TERRENCE SHINN AND FIRST MATE, CHARLIE LARA WERE ON THE BRIDGE AND MAINTAINING A LOOK OUT. THE SEAS WERE CALM, LESS THAN 1FT AND THE WIND WAS LESS THAN 10KTS. VISIBILITY WAS UNLIMITED. AT APPROXIMATELY 0830, THE FIRST MATE OBSERVED A SEA LION PORPOISING FOR A FEW SECONDS ALONG SIDE THE VESSEL IN THE WAKE, ROUGHLY MIDSHIP. IMMEDIATELY AFTERWARDS, THE VESSEL CREW FELT AN IMPACT ON THE PROPELLER AND IMMEDIATELY STOPPED THE VESSEL. THE SEA LION CARCASS WAS OBSERVED SINKING WITH BLOOD IN THE WATER. ESTIMATES OF SIZE AND LENGTH WERE DETERMINED AS IT WAS SINKING. THE SEA LION PORPOISING ALONG SIDE THE BOAT IS ASSUMED TO BE THE SEA LION THAT WAS STRUCK, HOWEVER SINCE IT WAS ONLY OBSERVED FOR A FEW SECONDS BEFORE THE IMPACT, IT CANNOT BE CONFIRMED. THERE WERE NO OTHER MARINE MAMMALS IN THE AREA AT THE TIME OF THE IMPACT. THE INCIDENT WAS IMMEDIATELY REPORTED TO CINMS VIA SATELLITE PHONE AND RECORDED IN THE VESSEL'S LOG.

Additional Remarks: Tag was infected because it was placed too far into tissues of flipper rather than closer to the edge. This is fourth infected tag we have noted in this series. Others include SBMMC-09-28 (23020), SBMMC-09-112(23023), and SBMMC-10-286 (23041). all four animals were emaciated yearlings. All four were imprinted and readily approached people on the beach. Two of the four animals were in such bad condition that they could not be saved. This animal SBMMC-10-314 came out of the water and rushed over to the rescue vehicle. We hesitate to mention this. Since 1976, such observations (consistent misapplied tags) have been rare and never in such a close sequence. These were the only animals in the 23000 series we rescued and every one had problems.

Other Human Int Description: Entangled in yellow 3/8 in polypro line
Additional Remarks: Report from Condor Express: On the way home one of our naturalists, John K., pointed out what appeared to be a dolphin in a clump of drift kelp. Upon inspection, it was indeed a dolphin. The crew pulled up alongside the lethargic dolphin with expert boat driving by captain Beezer. It was entangled in yellow 3/8 in polypro line, entangled around its mouth, back and pectoral flippers. It was dragging a mass of line behind it. After a few head thrashes by the dolphin, and some cutting of the line by the crew, the dolphin was eventually freed from the rope entanglement! The crew (Austin and Devin) were able to cut the animal free and release it unharmed with direction and boat handling skills by Captain Dave. https://www.facebook.com/condor.express/videos/442247232977562/
Observed by iNaturalist user: carinamotta
